Chinese Stocks in the U.S.: China Information, Cnooc, Deer Rise

-- B y   B e l i n d a   C a o
-- 
2011-09-16T20:51:52Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-16/chinese-stocks-in-the-u-s-china-information-cnooc-deer-rise.html
The Bank of New York Mellon  China 
ADR Index, which tracks American depositary receipts, slipped
0.2 percent to 392.52. The New York Stock Exchange China Index
retreated 0.3 percent to 238.65. The Shanghai Composite Index
added 0.1 percent to 2,482.34.  The following companies were among the most active Chinese
shares in New York trading. Stock symbols are in parentheses and
prices are as of the close of trading at 4 p.m. New York time.  China Information Technology Inc. (CNIT)   rose 4.1
percent, the most in seven trading sessions, to $1.27. The
Shenzhen, China-based  software company  said its board approved
to extend the company’s $5 million share repurchase plan,
previously announced Sept. 27, 2010, by one year to last for the
next 12 months.  Cnooc Ltd. (883)  , China’s largest offshore energy
producer, climbed 1.1 percent to a six-day high of $176.83. The
operator of the nation’s three liquefied natural gas terminals
may increase imports of the fuel via its Guangdong terminal by
16 percent this year to 6.5 million metric tons, said an
official at the facility, who declined to be named because of
company rules. The LNG will come from  Australia , Qatar, Total SA
and spot purchases, the official said.  PetroChina Co. (PTR US), the nation’s biggest oil producer,
gained 0.5 percent to $125.50. The company may increase
purchases of spot liquefied natural gas at its first import
terminal as demand rises during the colder months, said Liu
Wenfei, a director at the Jiangsu terminal. The terminal is
buying about two spot LNG cargoes a month as operations begin,
he said.  Deer Consumer Products Inc. (DEER)  , a China-based maker
of household products, leaped 9.3 percent, the most since June
23, to $5.04. The company is scheduled to pay shareholders on
Oct. 14 its quarterly cash dividend of 5 cents per share, it
said in a statement through PR Newswire today.  Giant Interactive Group Inc. (GA)  , a Chinese developer
of online role-playing video games, slid 1.6 percent to a record
low of $4.26. Its shareholders’ general meeting in  Hong Kong 
today approved the re-election of Andrew Y. Yan and Jason
Nanchun Jiang as directors of the company, Giant Interactive
said in a regulatory filing today. The meeting also appointed
Hua Ming at Ernst & Young as independent auditor for the fiscal
year 2011, it said.  To contact the reporter on this story:
